# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charlie-hemphill
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The **1899 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 through October 15, 1899, and saw the Brooklyn Superbas as the pennant winner of the National League.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 was the final season of a stable 12-team, eight-season run which saw no expansion or contraction of teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Following the end of the season, the National League contracted from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league Western League to position themselves as a major league in 1901, by beginning a transition from a Midwest-focused league to the nationwide focused American League.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 season is famous for the Cleveland Spiders finishing with the worst single-season record of all time (minimum 120 games), finishing at a dismal 20–134 (.130), largely due to the fact that the Spiders-owning Robison family bought the St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Perfectos prior to the 1899 season, then proceeded to move all Cleveland talent to St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, leaving the Spiders a talent-depleted team.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The only other major-league team of the 19th century with a worse record was the 1884 Wilmington Quicksteps, who entered the unstable single-season Union Association as a late-season replacement for the Philadelphia Keystones and played only 18 games, with a record of 2–16 (.111).
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns renamed as the Brooklyn Superbas and St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 schedule consisted of 154 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League in 1892 and the previous season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final season which saw this format, due to the reduction of teams the following season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 featuring four teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 15, featuring five teams play in four games (Chicago hosted Louisville and St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis hosted Chicago, while Cincinnati hosted Cleveland in a doubleheader).
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] 20 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Perfectos, New Sportsman's Park, is renamed League Park.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The home of the Louisville Colonels, Eclipse Park, was destroyed in a fire on August 12, while the team was on a road trip.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Following their return home, they would have a 12-game homestand from August 22 through September 2 in a partially rebuilt park, before spending the rest of the season on the road.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The **1902 major league baseball season** was contested from April 17 through October 5, 1902.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American League (AL), with the Philadelphia Athletics winning the AL pennant.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant for the second consecutive season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Milwaukee Brewers moved and became the St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns; the franchise would remain in St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis through 1953, and in 1954 moved again to become the modern Baltimore Orioles.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This season would be the last of this season's Baltimore Orioles, who would fold following the conclusion of the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues renamed as the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The 1902 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with every team playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 19, with a one-off game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Boston Americans, with the rest of the season beginning April 23.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 29, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games (8 in AL, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Across both leagues, Sammy Strang tied as a leader in runs at 109 (108 with the Chicago White Stockings of the AL and 1 with the Chicago Orphans of the NL).
[src:charlie-hemphill/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds leave League Park (where they played for 18 seasons) and move to the Palace of the Fans, where they would go on to play for ten seasons through 1911.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The **1904 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 to October 10, 1904.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans and New York Giants finished atop the standings for the American League and National League, respectively.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason: with still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues, the Giants declined to meet the Americans in the 1904 World Series.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the Americans were the defending World Series from the 1903 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns and Detroit Tigers played 11 consecutive games against each other in September—the first six in Detroit and the final five in St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis—the most games played consecutively between two teams in major league history.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings shortened their name to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The 1904 schedule consisted of 154 games (an increase from 140 from the previous season) for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 140-game, 20-games-each format that had been in place from the 1901 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League would see their final day of the regular season on October 9 & 10, respectively.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the New York Highlanders, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] 29 tie games (18 in AL, 11 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] With still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues regarding the staging of the World Series, the New York Giants refused to play against the Boston Americans or any other team from what they considered an inferior league.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators leave American League Park (where they played three seasons) and move into a new American League Park, where they would go on to play seven seasons through 1910.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Highlanders play one game at Wiedenmeyer's Park in Newark, New Jersey on Sunday, July 17, as a makeup between them and the Detroit Tigers and to avoid New York City's blue laws.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The **1906 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1906.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 7, with the Chicago Cubs and Chicago White Sox as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the third modern World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 6 on October 14.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The White Sox defeated the Cubs, four games to two, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1905 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The 1906 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 12 with all teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 14 with four teams playing.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 7.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 9 and October 14.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] 20 tie games (12 in AL, 8 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1906-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 14 with the Chicago White Sox defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1906 World Series in six games.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The **1907 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1907.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 12.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to none (with one tie), capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1906 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters renamed as the Boston Doves.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The 1907 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11 with all but the Brooklyn Superbas and Boston Doves playing.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 12.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (18 in AL, 12 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 12 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1907 World Series in five games (one of which being a tie).
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The **1908 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1908.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 8, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the prior year's postseason, the postseason began with Game 1 of the fifth modern World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to one, capturing their second championship in franchise history, and the first team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans renamed as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The 1908 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 14.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games (10 in AL, 6 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 14 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1908 World Series in five games.
[src:charlie-hemphill/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics would play their final game at Columbia Park with a doubleheader on October 3 against the Boston Red Sox, moving into Shibe Park for the start of the 1909 season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Hemphill was born in Greenville, Michigan.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] His younger brother, Frank Hemphill, also was an outfielder.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Basically a line-drive hitter, Hemphill entered the major leagues in 1899 with the St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Louis Perfectos, appearing in 11 games before joining the Cleveland Spiders during mid-season.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Louis and Cleveland clubs, both owned by the Robinson Brothers, proceeded to transfer the Spider's top players to St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Louis, leaving Cleveland with a truly awful club – they finished the 1899 season with a record of 20–134 which is the worst mark in major league history.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] The Spiders folded at the end of the season and, Hemphill went to the Kansas City Blues of the newly created American League in 1900; the AL was still considered a minor league that year.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] In 1901, Hemphill became the first opening day right fielder in the history of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] After that he played for the Cleveland Bronchos, St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Louis Browns and the New York Highlanders.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] His most productive season came in 1902, when he hit a combined .308 with Cleveland and St.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] He enjoyed another good season in 1908 with the Highlanders, hitting .298 with a career-high 42 stolen bases.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] His final season in the majors came in 1911 with the Highlanders, where he was a teammate of Chet Hoff, in what would be Hoff's only big-league campaign.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Hoff wound up being the longest-lived player in major league baseball history, finally passing away at the age of 107 in 1998–nearly a century after his old teammate Hemphill first played in the majors.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] In an 11-season career, Hemphill was a .271 hitter (1230-for-4541) with 22 home runs and 421 RBI in 1242 games, including 580 runs, 117 doubles, triples, 207 stolen bases, and a .337 on-base percentage.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] In 1175 outfield appearances, he played at center field (607), right (525) and left (45).
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] He also played three games at second base.
[src:charlie-hemphill/charlie-hemphill] Hemphill died in Detroit, Michigan, at age 77.
